One of my flatmates was working as a test-drive chauffeur for the London Bently & Rolls Royce dealer (Jack Barclays) at the time. If the showroom was shut when he finished with a customer, he had to take the car home (boo hoo) so he'd pick me up from work in uniform, in a brand new luxury car. My boss would wonder if they were paying me too much :-) Bently Turbo R was my favourite.

snippet.textDisplay: Great video as always Doug, have an awesome 2020 you and your wife and I hope you two had a great Christmas. That Turbo R looks so attractive with the monochrome bumpers and grill, the white contrasts beautifully with the beige leather, and interior with the black steering wheel. I love it with the chrome wheels. I've always loved the contrast of different woods, that burled maple and walnut. I'd bury my bare feet into that thick pile carpeting. It's cool to see the engine exposed like that. I found out that the 4 speed auto that Bentley started using was GM's 4L80E. It was a 4 speed version of their Turbo Hydromatic 400 with electronic overdrive used from 1992-97. I think that's cool because it's just before Vw's takeover in 1998 just like Bentley was different prior to Rolls Royce's take over in 1931.
snippet.textOriginal: Great video as always Doug, have an awesome 2020 you and your wife and I hope you two had a great Christmas. That Turbo R looks so attractive with the monochrome bumpers and grill, the white contrasts beautifully with the beige leather, and interior with the black steering wheel. I love it with the chrome wheels. I've always loved the contrast of different woods, that burled maple and walnut. I'd bury my bare feet into that thick pile carpeting. It's cool to see the engine exposed like that. I found out that the 4 speed auto that Bentley started using was GM's 4L80E. It was a 4 speed version of their Turbo Hydromatic 400 with electronic overdrive used from 1992-97. I think that's cool because it's just before Vw's takeover in 1998 just like Bentley was different prior to Rolls Royce's take over in 1931.
